On Saturday March 16 your department finally gave us our first designated resident parking spots at the ends of and on either side of Beacon Street running from Mass Ave to Charlesgate East.  They  also re-designated a few of the meters for thirty minute parking while re-designating all meters to run from 8 AM to 8 PM.  For the past two weeks we have not seen any meter readers patrolling our block.  They used to come shortly after 8 AM and they may or may not have returned later in the day.  I mention this because the other day I walked the length of our block and counted 7 cars parked in Resident Parking spots who did not have parking stickers.  I also counted 7 cars parked at expired meters, which assumes they paid for the first two hours which many drivers do not be true. Having waited years to get resident parking it is frustrating not to get access to them.  I do have one question: Are you permitted to give out tickets every two hours to the same vehicle who is in violation of parking restrictions? The reason I ask is that our block has always attracted Fenway park patrons who do not want to pay for the cost of parking lots in the area of the ball park.  The routinely arrive in the late afternoon and may or my not feed the meters.  Whether they get a ticket on not, which seldom occurs, it is still cheaper than paying $50 of more the parking lots charge. Thank you in advance for your consideration of the issues I have raised.

The fire marshal that shows up for each Roadrunner venue event told me that the reason there is no parking on this street is because the street is super narrow for fire trucks. I've made the point to the construction workers that parking is free on North Beacon Street during the day time, & it is literally only 150-200FT away from where they keep parking illegally. I wouldn't begrudge their laziness if it wasn't for the fact that they are rude daily. Every single work day, 2-3 work vans are parking on the street & causing madness. They're also parking heavy equipment at times at 35 Hichborn Street in that buildings rear parking lot, which is a private business lot.
